{{Kings of Judah}}
'''Abijam'''{{efn|{{hebrew Name|אֲבִיָּם|Aviyam|Āḇîyām| "father of the sea" or "my father is the sea"}}; {{lang-el|Αβιου|Aviou}}; {{lang-la|Abiam}})<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlbible.com/1_kings/15-1.htm|title=1 Kings 15:1 Multilingual: Now in the eighteenth year of King Jeroboam the son of Nebat, Abijam began to reign over Judah.|website=mlbible.com}}</ref>}} was, according to the [[Hebrew Bible]], the fourth king of the [[Davidic line|House of David]] and the second of the [[Kingdom of Judah]]. He was the son of [[Rehoboam]] and the grandson of [[Solomon]].{{sfn|Pulkrabek|2007|p=39}}{{sfn|Provan|Hubbard|Johnston|2012|p=189}}{{sfn|Zucker|2013|p=194}} The [[Chronicler]] refers to him as '''Abijah'''.{{efn|{{Hebrew Name 1|אֲבִיָּה|ʼĂḇiyyāh|"my father is [[Tetragrammaton|Yah]]"}}; {{lang-el|Αβια}}; {{lang-la|Abia}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlbible.com/2_chronicles/12-16.htm|title=2 Chronicles 12:16 Multilingual: And Rehoboam slept with his fathers and was buried in the city of David, and Abijah his son reigned in his place.|website=mlbible.com}}</ref>}}

==Family==
Abijam is reported in the books of [[Books of Kings|Kings]] and [[Books of Chronicles|Chronicles]] as being related to [[Maacah]], Micaiah, and King [[Asa of Judah]]. Scholars have found the biblical accounts of Abijam's family to be [[Internal consistency of the Bible|contradictory]].{{sfn|Sweeney|2007|p=191}} While a number of theories have been suggested,{{sfn|Myers|1965|p=79}}{{sfn|Falk|1996|p=145-147}}{{sfn|Tenney|Silva|2010|p=30}}{{efn|Note also the testimony of [[Josephus]]: "Asa his son succeeded in the kingdom; and the young man's mother was Michaiah." {{harv|Josephus|1737|loc=VII.11.3 |p=231}} }} no explanation can accommodate all available sources or has proved definitively compelling.{{sfn|Japhet|1993|p=671|quote=no one solution can encompass all the evidence}}{{sfn|Arbeli|1985|p=165-170}} Abijah married [[Polygamy|fourteen wives]], and had 22 sons and 16 daughters.<ref>{{bibleverse|2|Chronicles|13:21|HE}}</ref>

==Abijah in the Hebrew Bible==
===Reign of Abijah===
Following the death of [[Rehoboam]], his son Abijah succeeded the throne as [[Kingdom of Judah|King of Judah]].{{sfn|Merrill|2008|p=347}} He began his three-year reign (2 Chr. 12:16; 13:1, 2) with a strenuous but unsuccessful effort to bring back the ten tribes of the [[Kingdom of Israel (Samaria)|northern Kingdom of Israel]] to their allegiance.{{sfn|Easton|1894|p=6, Abi’jah (5.)}}

Following Abijah's ascension to the throne in the 18th year of [[Jeroboam|King Jeroboam I]] of Israel, he marched north with the purpose of winning Israel back to the Davidic kingdom.{{sfn|Merrill|2008|p=347}} Jeroboam surrounded Abijah's army, engaging in the [[battle of Mount Zemaraim]].{{sfn|Merrill|2008|p=347}} Abijah captured the Israelite cities of [[Old Gate (Jerusalem)|Jeshanah]], [[Ophrah|Ephron (''et-Taiyibeh'')]] and [[Bethel]].{{sfn|Merrill|2008|p=347}}

==Commentaries==
According to the [[Deuteronomist#Deuteronomistic history|Deuteronomist]],{{sfn|Eerdmans|2000|p=6, ABIJAH 3.}} "God gave him a lamp in [[Jerusalem]] by raising up a son to succeed him" (1 Kings 15:4). The wording in the [[Septuagint]] is "the Lord gave him a remnant".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biblehub.com/sep/1_kings/15.htm|title=1 Kings 15 Brenton Septuagint Translation|website=biblehub.com}}</ref> Thus the unconditional covenant blessing of [[Yahweh]] guaranteed his promise to [[King David]], to stabilize the Kingdom of David despite its ruler. The [[Books of Chronicles|Chronicler]] also emphasizes Yahweh's promise as seen by Abijah's success against every effort by Jeroboam to defeat him.{{sfn|Merrill|2008|p=347}} "Judah prevailed because they relied upon the Lord God of their fathers." (2 Chr. 13:18) God gave the Kingdom to David and his descendants (1 Chr. 17:14) by a [[covenant of salt]], meaning, of permanence (cf. Leviticus 2:13).{{sfn|Wycliffe|1962|p=873}}

== Chronological discrepancies==
According to {{bibleverse|2|Chronicles|13:1-2|HE}}, Abijah became king of Judah in the 18th year of the reign of [[Jeroboam]], and reigned for three years.

[[William F. Albright]] has dated his reign to 915–913 BCE.

[[Edwin R. Thiele|E. R. Thiele]] offers the dates 914/913 &ndash; 911/910 BCE.{{sfn|Thiele|1951|p=81, 82, 217}} As explained in the [[Rehoboam]] article, Thiele's chronology for the first kings of Judah contained an internal inconsistency that later scholars corrected by dating these kings one year earlier, so that Abijah's dates are taken as 915/914 to 912/911 BCE in the present article.

